{"id":"227728189_Three_Options_Are_Optimal_for_Multiple-Choice_Items_A_Meta-Analysis_of_80_Years_of_Research","abstract":"Multiple-choice items are a mainstay of achievement testing. The need to adequately cover the content domain to certify achievement proficiency by producing meaningful precise scores requires many high-quality items. More 3-option items can be administered than 4- or 5-option items per testing time while improving content coverage, without detrimental effects on psychometric quality of test scores. Researchers have endorsed 3-option items for over 80 years with empirical evidenceâ€”the results of which have been synthesized in an effort to unify this endorsement and encourage its adoption.","authors":["Michael C. Rodriguez"],"meta":["June 2005Educational Measurement Issues and Practice 24(2):3 - 13","DOI:10.1111/j.1745-3992.2005.00006.x"],"references":["247727304_What's_Wrong_with_Three-Option_Multiple_Choice_Items","326436708_An_Appropriate_Number_of_Multiple-Choice_Item_Alternatives_A_Difference_of_Opinion","289964219_Introduction_to_Classical_and_Modern_Test_Theory","268260552_Statistical_Issues_1_Statistical_Issues_of_Reliability_Generalization_and_an_Application_to_Achievement_Data","266274894_The_Art_Science_of_Item-Writing_A_Meta-Analysis_of_Multiple-Choice_Item_Format_Effects_Item-Writing_Rules_ii_Acknowledgments","264671440_Multiple_choice_tests_Power_length_and_optimal_number_of_choices_per_item","258123929_The_Reliability_Discrimination_and_Difficulty_of_Word-Knowledge_Tests_Employing_Multiple_Choice_Items_Containing_Three_Four_or_Five_Alternatives","254090556_Three-Choice_Versus_Four-Choice_Items_Implications_for_Reliability_and_Validity_Of_Objective_Achievement_Tests1","252201362_Information_Transmission_with_Elementary_Auditory_Displays","248981225_Some_Effects_of_Changes_in_Question_Structure_and_Sequence_on_Performance_in_a_Multiple_Choice_Chemistry_Test","248940785_Test_Item_Development_Validity_Evidence_From_Quality_Assurance_Pr